</section>

<section class="mission-details">
	<div class="mission-intro">
		
		<a name="eztoc19726788_1" id="eztoc19726788_1"></a><h2><b>The mission</b></h2><p>Aeolus was the first satellite mission to acquire profiles of Earth’s wind on a global scale.&nbsp;These observations improved weather forecasts and climate models. The Aeolus satellite carried just one large instrument – a Doppler wind lidar that measured the winds sweeping around our planet.&nbsp;Surpassing scientific expectations and exceeding its planned life in orbit, the mission ended on 28 July 2023.</p>
	</div>
	<div class="mission-data">
		
		<a name="eztoc19727811_1" id="eztoc19727811_1"></a><h2><b>The launch</b></h2>
<ul>

<li><b>Date: </b>22&nbsp;August 2018</li>

<li><b>Site:&nbsp;</b>Kourou, French Guiana</li>

<li><b>Rocket: </b>Vega</li>

</ul>

	</div>
	</section>

<section class="mission-stats connecting-benefiting">
	
		
		
<ul>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Aeolus/Lasers_in_space" target="_blank"><b>1st </b></a>wind lidar in space</li>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/FutureEO/Aeolus/Lasers_in_space"><b>7 billion</b></a>&nbsp;UV pulses</li>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/FutureEO/Aeolus/Aeolus_a_historic_end_to_a_trailblazing_mission" target="_blank"><b>5 years</b></a>&nbsp;in orbit</li>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/ESA_Multimedia/Images/2022/10/Aeolus_Value_of_Information" target="_blank"><b>3 billion</b></a>&nbsp;euros societal benefit</li>

</ul>

	
